"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453724","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Government has not made any assessment of the financial impact that leaving the EU would have on agriculture in Britain and Northern Ireland.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-25T15:57:40Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453724/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453724/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453724/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-22","Agriculture","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, whether her Department has made an assessment of the potential financial effect of leaving the EU on agriculture in Britain and Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Baroness Ritchie of Downpatrick","South Down","Ms Margaret Ritchie","27595"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453725","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-26","<p>A ban on the use of wild animals in travelling circuses is a manifesto commitment and will be introduced as soon as parliamentary time allows. In the interim, the welfare of any wild animals still being used by travelling circuses in England is protected by the Welfare of Wild Animals in Travelling Circuses (England) Regulations 2012. During the 2015 circus touring season, 18 wild animals were licensed by Defra under the Regulations for use by two circuses.</p>","Camborne and Redruth","George Eustice",,"2016-02-26T14:23:41.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453725/answer","Biography information for George Eustice","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453725/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453725/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-22","Animal Welfare: Circuses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, when she plans to bring forward proposals to ban the use of wild animals in circuses.","false","Biography information for Kerry McCarthy","Bristol East","Kerry McCarthy","27601"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453726","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-25","<p>The spread of ash dieback has been progressing much as we expected. This is based on the scientific modelling of the outbreak undertaken by Cambridge University.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has a comprehensive surveillance programme in place to monitor the infection. The level of infection is widely variable in areas, with the south-east of England being worst affected. A map showing outbreaks is updated regularly and available online at: <a href="http://chalaramap.fera.defra.gov.uk/" target="_blank">http://chalaramap.fera.defra.gov.uk/</a></p><p> </p><p>Ash is the third most prevalent broadleaved species in GB woodlands (estimated stocked area of ash is 142,000 thousand hectares, with an estimated 126 million trees) and as a proportion of total UK woodlands is around 4.7 percent (142,000 hectares as a proportion of three million hectares). Ash is also very common in non-woodland settings and it is estimated that there are 27-60 million ash trees<sup><sup>[1]</sup></sup> in non-woodland environments (parks, gardens, lining roads and railways).</p><p> </p><p>Local effects on landscapes and woodlands will mostly be gradual and mitigated by other tree species taking the place of ash trees. Natural tolerance to the disease does exist and the UK is leading the way on the work to identify resistant strains.</p><p>[1] The Tree Council (2015): <em>Chalara in Non-Woodland Situations. Findings from a 2014 study. </em></p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-25T16:53:22.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453726/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453726/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453726/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-22","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what estimate she has made of (a) the geographical extent of ash dieback disease and (b) its effect upon woodland and the number of ash trees in the UK.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27802"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453727","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-25","<p>A series of research projects, jointly funded by Defra, has looked into the ecological impacts of ash dieback and investigated possible woodland management options which might ameliorate the problems caused by ash dieback. The results from this work have been published at:</p><p><a href="http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5273931279761408" target="_blank">http://publications.naturalengland.org.uk/publication/5273931279761408</a>.</p><p> </p><p>The research found that there are tree species that share ecological traits or support some of the species associated with ash trees. However, there is no single tree species that would be able to fill the niche provided by ash in terms of both its ecosystem characteristics and biodiversity contribution.</p><p> </p><p>The Forestry Commission provides advice to woodland managers about how best to manage and adapt to ash dieback, for example by planting a variety of tree species as diversity brings resilience to pests and diseases.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-25T16:59:31.13Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453727/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453727/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453727/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-22","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what assessment she has made of the ecological effect of ash dieback disease in rural areas.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27803"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453728","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-02-25","<p>Investing in research is one of our key commitments in response to ash dieback. We have invested over £21 million into tree health research and the UK is leading the way on the work to identify resistant strains. Defra funded research has already identified three genetic markers for tolerance. This is a significant first step in developing trees with tolerance to the disease and testament to the innovation and dedication of our world leading scientists.</p><p> </p><p>The Government-funded screening trial of 155,000 ash saplings is also unprecedented in its scope.</p><p> </p><p>Collectively, our research is investigating the genetic basis for natural tolerance and screening our native ash trees for genetic markers; work is also underway to further our understanding of the pathogen, how it spreads and local management approaches to protect individual, high value trees.</p>","Penrith and The Border","Rory Stewart",,"2016-02-25T17:06:56.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453728/answer","Biography information for Rory Stewart","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453728/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453728/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2016-02-22","Ash Dieback Disease","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs, what progress her Department has made in identifying ash trees with resistance to ash dieback disease; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27804"
