"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453731","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Information on the expenditure incurred for individual events is not kept centrally, so this information could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-25T16:17:09.38Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453731/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453731/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453731/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","Embassies: Christmas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what proportion of his Department's budget was spent on Christmas parties hosted by British embassies and consulates in (a) 2013-14 and (b) 2014-15; and what estimate he has made of such planned spending in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453732","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>The full cost of inward State Visits is borne by a number of different Government Departments. We do not yet have the costs borne by the Foreign and Commonwealth Office for the 2015 State Visit by the President of China. These will be published on the gov.uk website once available.</p>","Rochford and Southend East","James Duddridge",,"2016-02-26T13:14:11.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453732/answer","Biography information for James Duddridge","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453732/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453732/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","China: State Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, how much (a) the Government and (b) each government department spent on (i) arrangements and (ii) hospitality for the Chinese state visit in October 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","27617"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453733","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-26","<p>At the February European Council the Government negotiated a new settlement, giving the United Kingdom a special status in a reformed European Union. The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU.</p><p>The Government believes that the best context for friendly and constructive bilateral relations with the Republic of Ireland is common membership of a reformed European Union. A vote to leave the EU in the referendum would bring with it uncertainty across a range of issues.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-02-26T14:41:31.087Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453733/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453733/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453733/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453733/answer/previousversion/47339","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on relations between the UK and Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27750"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453734","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>We are aware of reports of alleged violations of International Humanitarian Law (IHL) in Syria. The UK supports the UN Commission of Inquiry on Syria, which is mandated by the Human Rights Council to investigate all alleged violations of international human rights law including those that may constitute crimes against humanity in Syria with a view to ensuring perpetrators are held to account. In addition, the UK co-sponsored a UN Security Council resolution to refer all those who are alleged to be responsible for war-crimes and crimes against humanity in Syria, regardless of affiliation, to the International Criminal Court. Russia and China chose to veto this resolution.</p>","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-25T16:23:58.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453734/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453734/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453734/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","Syria: Military Intervention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of whether Russian airstrikes in Syria have breached international humanitarian law.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","27747"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453735","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>I discussed the Bedouin in the Negev with Head of the Joint List MK Ayman Odeh during my visit to Israel on 18 February. Officials from our Embassy in Tel Aviv are following developments closely, and we continue to encourage the Israeli authorities and Bedouin communities to work together to identify satisfactory solutions.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2016-02-25T14:08:29.587Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453735/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453735/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453735/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","Israel: Bedouin","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether he has had discussions with the Israeli government on the displacement of Bedouin people from townships in the Negev.","false","Biography information for Dr Tania Mathias","Twickenham","Dr Tania Mathias","27755"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453736","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","The internal review is expected to be completed in the Spring. Its remit is to advise on how the FCO can be more expert, agile and focused on the Department’s key priorities. I expect the review to set out a vision of the organisation the FCO should be by 2020. The review is internal. No decision has yet been taken on publication.","Runnymede and Weybridge","Mr Philip Hammond",,"2016-02-25T16:59:52.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453736/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453736/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453736/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Departmental Responsibilities","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, pursuant to the Government's response to the Foreign Affairs Committee's First Special Report of Session 2015-16, published on 11 February 2016, HC816, when he expects the internal review of his Department to be completed; what the key priorities of his Department are on which that review will be focussed; and if he will publish the conclusions of that review.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","27748"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453737","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>We continue to urge the DPRK authorities, through both our Embassy in Pyongyang and the DPRK Embassy in London, to respond in detail to the contents of the Commission of Inquiry report, including the violence and exploitation of women that it documents. The DPRK continues to reject the Commission’s findings and will not engage on the detail of the Commission’s report.</p><p>Women trafficked out of the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea (DPRK) are among the most vulnerable of those who flee the country. We call on the DPRK to improve its appalling human rights record and create better conditions for its women. We regularly discuss our concerns about the DPRK with China, as I did with the Vice-Minister of the Chinese Communist Party, Chen Fengxiang, in December 2015. We will seek to include this issue in the next UK-China Human Rights Dialogue due to be held in April. We also work directly with the Chinese authorities on a number of projects to counter human trafficking, which seek to protect the most vulnerable from exploitation, abuse, neglect and violence.</p><p> </p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-25T17:05:35.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453737/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453737/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453737/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","North Korea: Sexual Offences","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, with reference to the Answer of 5 January 2015 to Question 219046, what response his Department has received from Democratic People's Republic of Korea authorities; and whether progress has been made on improving North Korean women's rights in China.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453738","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>We are aware of UK tour companies who operate in the North Korea. Given the closed nature of the regime there is very limited financial information from the Democratic People’s Republic of Korea’s (DPRK) government on how their nuclear and ballistic missile programme or elements of the regime responsible for human rights violations are funded.</p><p> </p>","East Devon","Mr Hugo Swire",,"2016-02-25T17:09:08.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453738/answer","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453738/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453738/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","North Korea: Weapons","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether UK-owned tour companies that operate in North Korea contribute financially to that country's nuclear and missile programmes or to elements of the Democratic People's Republic of Korea government responsible for human rights violations.","false","Biography information for Fiona Bruce","Congleton","Fiona Bruce","27825"
