"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453779","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>NHS England and the National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE) have jointly consulted on draft proposals on the future direction of the Cancer Drugs Fund (CDF). The consultation closed on 11 February 2016 and the responses received are being analysed and will inform the new way of working for the Fund. A consultation report will be published on NHS England’s website in due course.</p><p> </p><p>NICE is working closely with NHS England to support the new way of working for the CDF. NICE’s Board is expected to consider the proposed process and methods for the Fund at its next meeting in March.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-25T14:42:37.51Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453779/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453779/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453779/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-22","Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when he expects NICE to begin assessing (a) drugs for rare cancer and (b) cancer drugs under the proposed new Cancer Drugs Fund.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","27605"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453780","Department of Health","false","2016-02-24","<p>No such estimate has been made.</p><p><br> We have no current plans to make such an assessment. We know that gambling addiction can potentially have a harmful impact on both a person’s physical and mental wellbeing and problem gamblers can access services in primary care and secondary care including specialised mental health and addiction services.</p><p><br> The Prime Minister recently announced £1 billion to start a revolution in mental health, including £247 million to make sure that every emergency department has mental health support (following £30 million invested in 2015/16).</p><p> </p><p>Also, over £400 million for crisis resolution home treatment teams will help to improve the management of admissions to acute psychiatric inpatient care, as well as ensure the routine availability of 24/7 intensive home treatment support as a safe and effective alternative to hospitals.</p><p> </p><p>Commissioners must continue to increase investment in mental health services each year at a level which at least matches their overall allocation increase.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt","27615","2016-02-24T14:35:27.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453780/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453780/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453780/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-22","Gambling","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the cost to the NHS of gambling addiction in each of the last three years.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27589"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453781","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","27799","2016-02-25T14:48:55.243Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453781/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453781/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453781/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Death Certificates: Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many deaths were recorded for which an eating disorder was mentioned on the death certificate in (a) the UK and (b) England in each year since 2010-11.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27795"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453782","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>One of the aims set out in the Green Paper, <em>No voice unheard, no right ignored – a consultation for people with learning disabilities, autism and mental health conditions</em>, published in March 2015, is to ensure people’s ‘nearest relative’ under the Mental Health Act 1983 (MHA) is someone who is meaningful to them. We have no plans to specifically change the nearest relative definition in the MHA to include unmarried fathers once their children are aged over 18 years.</p><p> </p><p>This will ensure that people are able to choose their own ‘nearest relative’, who has specific legal responsibilities under the MHA. The current MHA definition of the nearest relative will be updated to be used as a default if necessary, when the person is unable to make a choice for some reason.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-25T10:30:37.603Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453782/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453782/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453782/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-22","Mental Health Act 1983","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, whether he plans to bring forward proposals to change the closest living relative definition in the Mental Health Act 1983 to include unmarried fathers once their children are aged 18.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453783","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>NHS England published its consultation <em>on Developing the mental health services for veterans in England</em> on 25 January 2016.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-25T14:41:03.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453783/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453783/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453783/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-22","Mental Health Services: Veterans","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, when the NHS England plans to publish its consultation on the future of mental health support for veterans of the armed forces, referred to in the NHS England Mental Health Taskforce.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27797"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453784","Department of Health","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Department is responsible for health and care in England only. Responsibility and therefore data relating to the rest of the United Kingdom are a matter for the Scottish Government, the Welsh Government and the Northern Ireland Assembly.</p><p> </p><p>The following table shows the number of finished admission episodes (FAEs) for England with a primary diagnosis of an eating disorder for the whole year April 2014 to March 2015 and provisional data by month from April to October 2015.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Month of<br> Admission</p></td><td><p>FAE<sup>*</sup></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014-15 total</p></td><td><p>2,876</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>April 2015</p></td><td><p>238</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>May 2015</p></td><td><p>230</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>June 2015</p></td><td><p>220</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>July 2015</p></td><td><p>204</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>August 2015</p></td><td><p>166</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>September 2015</p></td><td><p>176</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>October 2015</p></td><td><p>179</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>* FAEs are counted against the year or month in which the admission episode finishes. Admissions do not represent the number of patients, as a person may have more than one admission within the period.</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2016-02-25T14:39:59.193Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453784/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453784/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453784/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-02-22","Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many first admission episodes there were with a primary diagnosis of an eating disorder in (a) England and (b) the UK in (i) 2014-15 and (ii) each month in 2015-16 for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27798"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453785","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Reading East","Mr Rob Wilson","27795","2016-02-25T14:48:55.32Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453785/answer","Biography information for Mr Rob Wilson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453785/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453785/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-22","Eating Disorders","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many deaths there were in (a) the UK and (b) England for which an eating disorder was the underlying cause of death for deaths registered in each year between 2010 and the last year for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Luciana Berger","Liverpool, Wavertree","Luciana Berger","27799"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453786","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The average waiting time for a postal leave to remain application during the period of 05 October 2014 to 27 February 2015 was 82 calendar days. These dates have been selected to sit alongside published data and are based on operational performance reporting. The average is based on the average waiting times between the date a postal application is submitted and the length of time taken to despatch the decision to the applicant for all leave to remain routes.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T17:31:14.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453786/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453786/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453786/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Immigration: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the current average waiting time is for an application for leave to remain.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","27592"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453787","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>Statutory guidance is issued under section 113B(4A) of the Police Act 1997 in order to assist chief officers of police in making decisions to provide relevant non-conviction information and other intelligence from local police records for inclusion in enhanced Disclosure and Barring Service certificates. The Home Office introduced the first edition of this guidance on 10 September 2012 and the most recent revision came into force on 10 August 2015.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-29T16:57:03.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453787/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453787/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453787/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Vetting","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what guidelines her Department produces on the inclusion of non-conviction information or soft information on DBS forms.","false","Biography information for Steve Rotheram","Liverpool, Walton","Steve Rotheram","27587"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453788","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-29","<p>Sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 (only applies in England and Wales) makes it an offence to intentionally procure a miscarriage, including for a woman to procure her own miscarriage.</p><p> </p><p>The Abortion Act 1967 creates exceptions to the offences of procuring a miscarriage. The Act makes an abortion legal where the pregnancy is terminated by a registered medical practitioner and where two registered medical practitioners agree that the grounds specified in the Act are satisfied.</p><p> </p><p>The number of offenders found guilty at all courts for offences relating to sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Persons Act 1861, in England &amp; Wales, from 2009 to 2014 (the latest data available) can be viewed in the attached table.</p><p> </p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-29T12:12:16.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453788/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453788/answer","27599 table.xls","Offenders found guilty from 2009-14","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453788/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Abortion","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many people have been convicted of offences under sections 58 and 59 of the Offences Against the Person Act 1861 related to abortions in each year since 2009-10.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27599"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453789","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Home Office does not collect information centrally on the reasons why police officers are called out to specific locations. The Home Office has no plans for a formal assessment of the impact of fixed odds betting terminals on levels of crime.</p><p>It is for Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners to decide crime priorities at a local level, and the most appropriate response in their areas.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27650","2016-02-25T15:48:03.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453789/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453789/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453789/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Betting Shops: Crimes of Violence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many police call-outs to betting shops there were due to violence related to fixed odds betting terminals.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453790","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Home Office does not collect information centrally on the reasons why police officers are called out to specific locations. The Home Office has no plans for a formal assessment of the impact of fixed odds betting terminals on levels of crime.</p><p>It is for Chief Constables and Police and Crime Commissioners to decide crime priorities at a local level, and the most appropriate response in their areas.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning","27649","2016-02-25T15:48:03.367Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453790/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453790/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453790/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Gaming Machines: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, if she will make an assessment of the effect of fixed odds betting terminals on levels of crime; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Carolyn Harris","Swansea East","Carolyn Harris","27650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453791","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Robust operational plans are in place and are reviewed regularly to ensure Her Majesty’s Passport Office is able to process passport applications within the published service standards. The organisation's workforce and operational plans take account of demand cycles, and contingency measures are in place.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-25T15:46:31.663Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453791/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453791/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Passports: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department is taking to ensure that applications for passports are processed without delays over the peak summer period.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","27642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453792","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>This information is not held centrally and can only be collated at disproportionate cost.</p>","North West Cambridgeshire","Mr Shailesh Vara",,"2016-03-01T15:12:35.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453792/answer","Biography information for Mr Shailesh Vara","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453792/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453792/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Immigration: Judicial Review","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many consent orders have been signed by courts for the settlement of judicial review cases for asylum and immigration applications in each year since 2009-10; how many such cases were decided in favour of the appellant upon reconsideration; how many found in contempt of court for the breaching such consent orders; and on how many occasions the courts has refuse to sign a consent order.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453793","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>Home Office systems cannot be interrogated in a way that will provide any meaningful response to the question. A manual review of all applications submitted within the stipulated timeframe would be needed in order to provide an accurate response and this would incur a disproportionate cost to the public purse.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T17:35:32.75Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453793/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453793/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453793/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people with dependants who have been granted leave to remain in the UK had a no recourse to public funds condition attached to their leave in (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","27729"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453794","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>Home Office Systems cannot be interrogated in a way that will provide any meaningful response to the question. A manual review of all applications submitted with dependants within the stipulated timeframe would be needed in order to provide an accurate response and this would incur a disproportionate cost to the public purse.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T17:34:17.047Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453794/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453794/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453794/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Immigration: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many people under the age of 18 were dependants of adults who had been granted leave to remain in the UK and had also had a no recourse to public funds condition attached to their leave in the financial years (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","27730"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453795","Home Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The data requested is not available for each of the years requested and can only be provided from December 2014. The number of submitted applications for a change of conditions to allow recourse to public funds between December 2014 and 30 September 2015 is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>December 2014 – March 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>930</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>April 2015 – September 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>1660</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>This response represents the closest reply that can be provided within the constraints of our data reporting system.</p><p>The data provided is considered Management Information and is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of National Statistics.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-03T17:14:32.52Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453795/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453795/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453795/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many requests were made to her Department for a change of conditions of leave lifting the condition of no recourse to public funds in financial years (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","27731"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453796","Home Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The data requested is not available for each of the years requested and can only be provided from December 2014. The number of granted applications for a change of conditions to allow recourse to public funds between December 2014 and 30 September 2015 is as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Period</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Number of Granted Applications</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>December 2014 – March 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>235</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>April 2015 – September 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>680</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>This response represents the closest reply that can be provided within the constraints of our data reporting system.</p><p>The data provided is considered Management Information and is subject to change. It has not been assured to the standard of National Statistics.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-03T17:09:49.263Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453796/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453796/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453796/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Immigration","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many requests were made to her Department for a change of conditions of leave were approved in lifting the no recourse to public funds condition to the applicants conditions of leave in financial years (a) 2011-12, (b) 2012-13, (c) 2013-14 and (d) 2014-15.","false","Biography information for Mr David Lammy","Tottenham","Mr David Lammy","27732"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453797","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>We publish statistics on cases where the claimant’s age has been disputed and a formal age assessment has been carried out. The table below shows the number of cases in each of the last 3 years.</p><p> </p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td colspan="2"><p>Asylum Claims by Year with a disputed age</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Year of Claim</p></td><td><p>Totals</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2012</p></td><td><p>337</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2013</p></td><td><p>323</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>2014</p></td><td><p>318</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Data is taken from published statistics https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/immigration-statistics-july-to-september-2015/asylum</p><p>Whilst we do hold information on the results of these assessments and whether they were found to be under the age of 18 the way corresponding data is held means that to obtain the data could only be achieved at disproportionate cost by examination of individual case files.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-25T15:50:32.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453797/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453797/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453797/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Asylum: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what estimate her Department has made of the number of asylum seekers who have been found to have fraudulently claimed to be under the age of 18 in each of the last years.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","27788"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453798","Home Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Home Office does not maintain a central record of the requested information and could only provide it at disproportionate cost.</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-03-01T16:21:42.41Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453798/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453798/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453798/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Asylum: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many asylum seekers claiming to be under the age of 18 have been charged with a criminal offence in the last year; and what proportion of such asylum seekers were subsequently found to have fraudulently claimed to be under the age of 18.","false","Biography information for David T. C. Davies","Monmouth","David T. C. Davies","27789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453799","Home Office","false","2016-02-29","<p>The average length of time taken to consider an application for British citizenship in the period 1 October 2014 to 30 September 2015 was 108.89 calendar days. This is the most recent period for which statistics on the number of applications considered have been published. The service standard for citizenship applications is to decide 98.5% of cases within 6 months (183 calendar days).</p>","Old Bexley and Sidcup","James Brokenshire",,"2016-02-29T15:58:07.187Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453799/answer","Biography information for James Brokenshire","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453799/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453799/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","British Nationality: Applications","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what the average length of time was for an application for British citizenship from submission of initial application to decision in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Anne McLaughlin","Glasgow North East","Anne McLaughlin","27815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453800","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Home Office does not hold data centrally on the number of custody nurses employed by the Metropolitan Police. This information may be held by the Metropolitan Police Force.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-25T15:49:07.947Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453800/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453800/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453800/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Metropolitan Police: Nurses","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, how many custody nurses were employed by the Metropolitan Police (a) in total and (b) in each London borough in each year since 2010.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27769"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453801","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>a) The Home Office is not required to compile prompt payment data in respect of private companies. To calculate such a figure would incur disproportionate costs.</p><p>b) In the financial year 2014-15, 88% of the total numbers of all invoices to every type of supplier were paid within five working days of receipt. The total number of invoices paid within 30 working days of receipt of invoice was 97%.</p><p>For small and small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs), the Home Office paid 80% of invoices within five working days of receipt of invoice. And 96% of invoices from SMEs were paid within 30 working days of receipt of invoice.</p><p>i) The proportion of the number of contracts between the Home Office and SMEs is not readily available, except at disproportionate costs.</p><p>ii) In 2014-15, the Home Office have reported 19.6% spend with SMEs. This figure is made up of 7.7% (£200 million) direct spend with SMEs and 11.9% (£310 miliion) indirect spend.</p>","Staffordshire Moorlands","Karen Bradley",,"2016-02-25T16:25:51.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453801/answer","Biography information for Karen Bradley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453801/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453801/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Home Office: Billing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what proportion of her Department's invoices for goods and services supplied by (a) private companies and (b) small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) are completed on time; and what proportion of the (i) number and (ii) value of contracts between her Department and private companies are held by SMEs.","false","Biography information for Caroline Flint","Don Valley","Caroline Flint","27779"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453802","Home Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Department’s Fire Kills campaign, run in close partnership with fire and rescue authorities in England, promotes a range of domestic fire safety messages, including on electrical fire safety, to ensure householders take appropriate action to prevent accidental fires and understand how best they can protect themselves and their families.</p><p>Fire Kills and Electrical Safety First have a longstanding and close partnership to promote electrical fire safety messages, including through the annual Electrical Fire Safety Week, which runs in November each year.</p><p>The campaign also supports the Register My Appliance initiative, run by the Association of Manufacturers of Domestic Electrical Appliances. This is designed to improve recall rates and ensure a greater number of faulty products can be traced and either repaired or removed from homes.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-24T16:23:24.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453802/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453802/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453802/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Fires: Electrical Safety","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what steps her Department has taken to reduce the number of fires caused by an electrical source of ignition in domestic dwellings.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","27722"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453803","Home Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The evaluation of the recent Fire Kills Unsung Heroes campaign is currently underway and the results will be analysed and fed into future campaign development. The Fire Kills campaign is included in plans for 2016/17 subject to appropriate approvals from the Secretary of State.</p>","Hemel Hempstead","Mike Penning",,"2016-02-25T16:15:17.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453803/answer","Biography information for Sir Mike Penning","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453803/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453803/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-02-22","Fire Prevention","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, what plans her Department has for the future of its Fire Kills campaign.","false","Biography information for Jim Fitzpatrick","Poplar and Limehouse","Jim Fitzpatrick","27723"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453804","House of Commons Commission","false","2016-02-29","<p>Service charges paid by debit and credit cards are passed on to catering staff employed by the House of Commons in addition to their wages through the House of Commons payroll system. They are shared equally amongst staff working on a particular day in a given venue.</p><p>Agency (contracted) workers do not receive service charge amounts as there is no mechanism for these to be paid to the individual as the agencies are paid separately to the House of Commons payroll system.</p>","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake",,"2016-02-29T16:03:43.737Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453804/answer","Biography information for Tom Brake","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453804/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453804/answer",,,,,"18","House of Commons Commission","House of Commons Commission","2016-02-22","House of Commons: Catering","1","House of Commons","To ask the hon. Member for Carshalton and Wallington representing the House of Commons Commission, what the Commission's policy is on the allocation of service charges paid by card to (a) permanent and (b) contracted canteen and hospitality staff working on the parliamentary estate.","false","Biography information for Tulip Siddiq","Hampstead and Kilburn","Tulip Siddiq","27612"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453805","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-26","<p>The meeting at the World Health Organisation (WHO) has been postponed to May 2016 and arrangements about the meeting are at an early stage. DFID officials are engaging with WHO on their plans.</p><p>The UK Government priority is to see a Pooled Fund for Research and Development established with support from WHO Member States, especially those that have not yet provided funding for this type of work. The UK Government supports systems that separate the market incentives to produce a drug or vaccine, from the Research &amp; Development process, prioritise public health need over profit and work in partnership with a wide range of different organisations, covering the public, private and philanthropic sectors. The UK is the second largest government supporter of product development partnerships, which prioritise need over profit, and have a proven track record in developing new products.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-26T14:27:14.993Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453805/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453805/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453805/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-22","Drugs: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what the Government plans to do to support reforms to research and development of pharmaceuticals at the World Health Organisaiton meeting in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Maynard","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","27784"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453806","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>As outlined in the response to PQ (House of Commons written), Hansard ref 27784; the meeting at the World Health Organisation (WHO) has been postponed to May 2016 and arrangements about the meeting are at an early stage. DFID officials are in discussion with WHO senior managers about UK representation at the meeting.</p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T17:47:38.043Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453806/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453806/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453806/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-22","Drugs: Research","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, who the Government plans to send as its representative to the discussions on research and development of pharmaceuticals at the World Health Organisation meeting in March 2016.","false","Biography information for Paul Maynard","Blackpool North and Cleveleys","Paul Maynard","27785"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453807","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>DFID has a significant programme of ongoing support in health, education, agriculture, water and sanitation and economic development, particularly in rural areas and with the private sector, for growth, jobs, incomes and food insecurity in Malawi. We support increasing access to justice for women and vulnerable groups, accountability and governance reforms.</p><p> </p><p>The UK was one of the first development partners to respond to Malawi’s international appeal for emergency aid in October 2015. The UK has now committed £14.5m through partners including the World Food Programme, UNICEF and an International Non-Governmental Organisation (INGO) consortium led by Save the Children. This support includes:</p><p> </p><ul><li>Food for over 800,000 people, including pre-positioning of food, nutrition supplies and livestock vaccines.</li><li>Cash transfers for up to 450,000 people who live near functioning markets but do not have the means to purchase food</li><li>Mass screening of up to 800,000 children to identify urgent nutritional support needs</li><li>Specialist supplies for over 140,000 children and others suffering from acute malnutrition</li><li>Vital protection support to vulnerable people, including women and girls, in displacement and refugee camps</li></ul>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T17:47:16.57Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453807/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453807/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453807/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-22","Malawi: Malnutrition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assistance  her Department plans to provide to help tackle hunger in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","27786"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453808","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-25","<p>No UK aid goes directly through Nigerian government systems. Our bilateral aid is delivered through commercial service providers (private sector), international organisations and non-governmental organisations (NGOs).</p><p>The table below provides a breakdown of our payments over financial years 2012-13 to 2014-15.</p><table><tbody><tr><td> </td><td><p><strong>2012/13</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2013/14</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Private Sector</p></td><td><p>£145.724m</p></td><td><p>£185.146m</p></td><td><p>£156.147m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>International Organisations</p></td><td><p>£31.905m</p></td><td><p>£52.343m</p></td><td><p>£40.505m</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NGOs</p></td><td><p>£22.401m</p></td><td><p>£28.498m</p></td><td><p>£27.667m</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-25T16:06:45.623Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453808/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453808/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453808/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-22","Nigeria: Overseas Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what proportion of her Department's spending was allocated to (a) Nigerian state organisations, (b) non-governmental organisations and (c) the private sector in the last three years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Chi Onwurah","Newcastle upon Tyne Central","Chi Onwurah","27734"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453809","Department for International Development","false","2016-02-29","<p>Each year the Malawi Vulnerability Assessment Committee (MVAC) assesses food availability in Malawi and publishes the official figure for those who are likely to be food insecure over the year. This year, at over 2.8m people, the figure is the highest for a decade. The UK was one of the first development partners to respond to Malawi’s international appeal for emergency aid in October 2015. The UK has now committed £14.5m, which includes provision of food for over 800,000 people, mass screening of up to 800,000 children to identify urgent nutritional support needs and specialist nutrition supplies for over 140,000 children and others suffering from acute malnutrition.</p><p> </p><p>DFID continues to monitor the situation, through formal assessments, community consultation and ongoing engagement with partners. Maize prices are high and increasing and food availability on markets is unpredictable. The Government of Malawi has released maize from its reserves and has bought additional supplies from Zambia, although there are ongoing concerns about effectiveness of its distribution. DFID continues to work with partners to help Malawi break the cycle of recurrent food insecurity crises year after year.</p><p> </p>","Ruislip, Northwood and Pinner","Mr Nick Hurd",,"2016-02-29T17:48:13.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453809/answer","Biography information for Mr Nick Hurd","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453809/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453809/answer",,,,,"20","International Development","International Development","2016-02-22","Malawi: Food","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Development, what assessment her Department has made of the availability of food to people in Malawi.","false","Biography information for Mr Andrew Smith","Oxford East","Mr Andrew Smith","27787"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453810","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>The information requested can only be provided at a disproportionate cost.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-25T16:30:48.683Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453810/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453810/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453810/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Prisons: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many key lock incidents there have been in each month since May 2010; how many such incidents related to doors of gates left unlocked; and in which establishments those incidents took place.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27832"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453811","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-04-12","<p>I refer the Hon Member to the answer for PQ 20749. The table attached provides a further breakdown of the data provided in that PQ.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of incidents at height are minor in nature and resolved quickly and professionally without injury, damage or disruption to the running of the prison. Many are short in duration, lasting less than 15 minutes and the majority occur when prisoners go onto netting on prison wings. Each incident is investigated fully to ensure lessons are learnt and best practice in managing incidents is shared across NOMS.</p><p> </p><p>These figures show that the Prime Minister and Justice Secretary are right and our prisons badly need reform. We are making progress: we have made it illegal to smuggle new psychoactive substances (NPS) into prisons and have trained over 300 sniffer dogs to detect NPS and are trialling the use of body worn cameras with front-line staff. But the only way to reduce disorder and violence in our prisons is to give those who work in prisons the tools necessary to better reform and rehabilitate offenders.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-04-12T14:14:58.757Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453811/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453811/answer","27833 Incidents at Heights 2010-16.xlsx","Incidents at Heights 2010-16","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453811/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Prisons: Discipline","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents at height in respect of each method of access there have been in each prison in each month since May 2010.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27833"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453812","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>Finds of certain prohibited items in prisons, including knives, are recorded on the NOMS Incident Reporting System (IRS).</p><p>Until October 2015, any weapon in prison would be recorded under a miscellaneous incident type, and therefore would not provide consistent and complete information on weapon finds. In October 2015 we introduced a new incident type ‘Find’ on IRS, including a new category for ‘Weapons’, which means that separate data on weapons is now recorded.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","27812","2016-02-25T16:41:24.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453812/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453812/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453812/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Prisons: Knives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 14 January 2016 to Question 21315, whether the changes to the Incident Report System of September 2015 made any improvements to the recording of knife finds.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453813","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>We had already recognised the issues highlighted in the 2014-15 Annual Report of the Independent Monitoring Board at HM Prison Belmarsh. I am pleased to inform the hon. Member for Erith and Thamesmead that we will be increasing the number of social visit slots that are available per session and we have added an additional booking telephone line. There are also plans to introduce an automated system to increase our capacity to manage visit calls.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-25T16:36:40.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453813/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453813/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453813/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Belmarsh Prison: Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken in response to the findings set out in the 2014-15 Annual Report of the Independent Monitoring Board at HM Prison Belmarsh on the prison's online and telephone booking system.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","27808"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453814","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>Finds of certain prohibited items in prisons, including knives, are recorded on the NOMS Incident Reporting System (IRS).</p><p>Until October 2015, any weapon in prison would be recorded under a miscellaneous incident type, and therefore would not provide consistent and complete information on weapon finds. In October 2015 we introduced a new incident type ‘Find’ on IRS, including a new category for ‘Weapons’, which means that separate data on weapons is now recorded.</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous","27813","2016-02-25T16:41:24.077Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453814/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453814/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453814/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Prisons: Knives","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26908, what steps he is taking to improve the recording of knife finds in prisons to ensure that the data is easy to use and analyse.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453815","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-03-01","<p>On 19 February, the Prime Minister set out the Government position on remaining in the European Union.</p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-03-01T15:27:56.433Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453815/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453815/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453815/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what research his Department has (a) commissioned and (b) conducted on the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on (a) relationships between his Department and its counterparts in other EU member states and (b) the effectiveness of pan-European justice mechanisms; and what assessment his Department has made of the results of that research.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27728"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453816","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Freedom of Information Act does not require the Ministry of Justice to publish all our responses to Freedom of Information requests. The Ministry of Justice maintains a disclosure log on GOV.UK, and we review what is published on the log on an ongoing basis: <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/freedom-of-information-disclosure-log#history" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/freedom-of-information-disclosure-log#history</a></p>","Esher and Walton","Dominic Raab",,"2016-02-25T16:53:59.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453816/answer","Biography information for Dominic Raab","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453816/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453816/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Ministry of Justice: Freedom of Information","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, for what reason not all the monthly announcements of Freedom of Information releases for 2015 have been published on his Department's website.","false","Biography information for Andy Slaughter","Hammersmith","Andy Slaughter","27756"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453817","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>The relevant data requested is attached.</p><p> </p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T16:24:50.117Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453817/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453817/answer","Attachment to 27771.xls","New registered proprietor entry ","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453817/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Property: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many properties that have been bought and sold in (a) London and (b) each London borough in the last 10 years record no sale price on the Land Registry.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27771"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453818","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>The relevant data is attached.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:21:59.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453818/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453818/answer","Attachment to 27772.xls","New registered proprietor entry with no registered","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453818/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-22","Foreign Companies: Property","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many properties in (a) England and Wales, (b) London and (c) each London Borough are registered with the Land Registry (i) in total and (ii) to off-shore companies.","false","Biography information for Sadiq Khan","Tooting","Sadiq Khan","27772"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453819","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>Family and legal visits have been cancelled on two occasions in the last 12 months at HM Prison Belmarsh. These were;</p><p> </p><p>8 October 2015 – Due to a full lock down search of the prison</p><p>9 December 2015 – To enable a Trade Union meeting</p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-25T12:55:29.827Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453819/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453819/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453819/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Belmarsh Prison: Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many times (a) family and (b) legal visits to prisoners in HM Prison Belmarsh have been cancelled in each of the last 12 months; and for what reason each such visit was cancelled.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","27766"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453820","Ministry of Justice","false","2016-02-25","<p>Maintaining family ties, including through visits, plays a vital role in helping prisoners turn away from crime.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All convicted prisoners are entitled to a minimum of two visits every 28 days and this has not changed since 1992. Extra visits can also be granted.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>The Public Sector Prisons benchmark provides prisons with a core day and staffing resource to deliver all required activities and services. Part of the benchmark provision is the delivery of social and legal visits and there is an expectation that these are critical activities which will not be cancelled.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South West Bedfordshire","Andrew Selous",,"2016-02-25T17:23:03.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453820/answer","Biography information for Andrew Selous","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453820/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453820/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2016-02-22","Prisons: Visits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what steps he has taken to prevent family and legal visits being cancelled in prisons in England and Wales; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Teresa Pearce","Erith and Thamesmead","Teresa Pearce","27765"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453821","Leader of the House","false","2016-03-01","<p><strong>No substantive discussions have taken place. Agendas and decisions relating to meetings of the House of Commons Commission are available on their website at <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/house-of-commons-commission/" target="_blank">http://www.parliament.uk/business/committees/committees-a-z/other-committees/house-of-commons-commission/</a>.</strong></p>","Epsom and Ewell","Chris Grayling",,"2016-03-01T15:16:43.997Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453821/answer","Biography information for Chris Grayling","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453821/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453821/answer",,,,,"34","Leader of the House","Leader of the House","2016-02-22","House of Commons: Repairs and Maintenance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Leader of the House, what discussions he has had with the House of Commons Commission on the potential effect on staffing and other costs and expenditure on repair and maintenance contracts of uncertainty about the dates of 2016 parliamentary recesses.","false","Biography information for Lord Mann","Bassetlaw","John Mann","27623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453822","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>There are long-established and effective working relationships between the police and intelligence agencies of the UK and Ireland to mitigate threats in both countries. The UK Government takes protecting our border security very seriously and there is a high level of co-operation and on-going work with the Irish Government strengthening the external border of the Common Travel Area.</p><p> </p>","Chipping Barnet","Mrs Theresa Villiers",,"2016-02-25T14:26:37.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453822/answer","Biography information for Theresa Villiers","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453822/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453822/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-22","Borders: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the implications for border security arrangements of recent gangland-related murders in the Irish Republic.","false","Biography information for Mr Gregory Campbell","East Londonderry","Mr Gregory Campbell","27641"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453823","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. ‘The best of both worlds’, published on 22 February, sets out how membership of the EU enhances our ability to co-operate with other EU Member States to combat crime and terrorism and keep all parts of the United Kingdom safe, including Northern Ireland.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The paper is available at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union</a><strong>.</strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-02-25T12:58:33.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453823/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453823/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453823/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what assessment she has made of the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on security in Northern Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27751"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453824","Northern Ireland Office","true","2016-02-25","<p><del class="ministerial">The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. ‘The best of both worlds’, published on 22 February, sets out how membership of the EU enhances our ability to co-operate with other EU Member States to combat crime and terrorism and keep all parts of the United Kingdom safe, including Northern Ireland.</del></p><p> </p><p><del class="ministerial">The paper is available at:</del></p><p><del class="ministerial"><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/the-best-of-both-worlds-the-united-kingdoms-special-status-in-a-reformed-european-union</a><strong>.</strong></del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">Government Ministers have regular discussions with Ministers from the Government of Ireland on a range of issues, including co-operation on security and other matters.</ins></p><p> </p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-02-25T12:56:42.767Z","2016-02-25T14:41:51.333Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453824/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453824/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453824/answer","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453824/answer/previousversion/47087","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with Irish Ministers on the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on security in (a) Northern Ireland and (b) Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27752"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453825","Northern Ireland Office","false","2016-02-25","<p>Government Ministers have regular discussions with Ministers from the Government of Ireland on a range of issues, including co-operation on security and other matters.</p>","Wyre and Preston North","Mr Ben Wallace",,"2016-02-25T13:03:25.35Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453825/answer","Biography information for Mr Ben Wallace","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453825/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453825/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU: Republic of Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what discussions she has had with Irish Ministers on the potential effect of a UK withdrawal from the EU on relations with Ireland.","false","Biography information for Tom Brake","Carshalton and Wallington","Tom Brake","27753"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453826","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-03-01","<p>At the February European Council, the Government negotiated a new settlement giving the UK a special status in a reformed EU.</p><p>The Government's view is that the UK will be stronger, safer and better off remaining in a reformed EU. The UK does intend to pass domestic legislation where necessary to underpin this settlement, following a vote to remain in the EU in the referendum.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2016-03-01T17:33:45.973Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453826/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453826/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453826/answer","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453826/answer/previousversion/47340","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-02-22","UK Membership of EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, whether the Government plans to introduce legislative proposals related to the agreement reached on the UK's relationship with the EU at the European Council on 19 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","27644"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453827","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Elizabeth line, being constructed by Crossrail, will be a high-frequency metro-style train service, and will carry an estimated 200 million passengers a year.</p><p> </p><p>The vast majority of journeys will be of a short duration and on board toilets would take up a significant amount of space.</p><p> </p><p>It is therefore not intended that toilets will be provided on the new trains as these would displace approximately 600 passengers per hour. 80 per cent of stations on the Elizabeth line will have toilet facilities.</p>","Devizes","Claire Perry",,"2016-02-25T16:31:56.467Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453827/answer","Biography information for Claire Perry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453827/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453827/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Crossrail Line: Sanitation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the planned availability of toilet facilities is (a) on Crossrail trains and (b) at Crossrail train stations.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","27646"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453828","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Government takes the unacceptable actions of Volkswagen extremely seriously and our priority is to protect the public. In Europe, Volkswagen Group has developed a technical solution for the affected vehicles and is testing this with the relevant type approval authorities. For Skoda vehicles this is the UK’s Vehicle Certification Agency. We understand that the company is not in the same position in the USA as there is not yet an agreed technical solution. We are urging Volkswagen to complete swiftly the recall of the affected vehicles in the UK.</p><p> </p><p>In his appearance before the Transport Select Committee on 25 January, Paul Willis, the CEO of Volkswagen UK, reconfirmed that Volkswagen do not intend to offer compensation in the UK as they do not believe that vehicle owners have suffered a loss. In the USA they have offered their customers up to $1,000 in gift vouchers. It is for Volkswagen to justify to their customers the different approaches that they are taking in different jurisdictions, however the Government expects Volkswagen to treat its UK customers fairly and the Secretary of State continues to press Volkswagen on the issue of this discrepancy in compensation.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-01T12:36:19.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453828/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453828/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453828/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Volkswagen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what information his Department holds on the distinctions between Volkswagen's practices (a) on the use of defeat devices and (b) in mitigating customer inconvenience in the US and the UK; and whether his Department has made an assessment of the reasons for those distinctions.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27610"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453829","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>Ministers and officials in the Department for Transport regularly meet with both Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs and Highways England on measures to improve air quality, public health and achieve compliance with EU air quality standards. On 17 December 2015 Government published the Air Quality Action Plan which sets out a comprehensive approach for meeting these goals. Air Quality is a clear priority for Highways England, backed up by a dedicated £100 million fund as part of the Road Investment Strategy published in December 2014.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-01T15:11:28.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453829/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453829/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453829/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Air Pollution","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what discussions he has had with the Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs on measures to improve air quality; and what discussions he has had with Highways England on the level of priority it accords to issues of air quality.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453830","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Department for Transport (DfT) is responsible for ensuring that proportionate security measures are in place to protect ports, passengers and ships registered in this country. These measures are risk based and are designed to mitigate the threat from terrorism. This work involves close co-operation with other government departments, the Police and the maritime industry.</p><p> </p><p>The Home Office is responsible for the detection of contraband and trafficked persons at UK Ports. DfT works closely with the Home Office and other partner agencies to counter this type of illegal activity.</p>","Scarborough and Whitby","Mr Robert Goodwill",,"2016-03-01T15:10:20.81Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453830/answer","Biography information for Mr Robert Goodwill","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453830/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453830/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Ports: Security","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, which Government policies on ensuring the (a) security of UK ports and (b) identification and checking of containers for contraband, trafficked persons or other illegal activity are the responsibility of his Department; and which such policies which are the responsibility of another department his Department has a secondary role in.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453831","Department for Transport","false","2016-03-01","<p>The Department considers that the number of drivers potentially affected by the extension of the radius from 50km to 100km covering one directly applicable exemption and three national derogations from the EU drivers’ hours rules is likely to be relatively small.</p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-03-01T15:08:54.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453831/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453831/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453831/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-22","Large Goods Vehicle Drivers: Working Hours","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what estimate his Department has made of the number of drivers potentially affected by the extension of the radius from 50km to 100km from base within which vehicles are exempt from regulations limiting drivers' hours.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27819"
