"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453874","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>Please see table below for Short Term Benefit Advance (STBA) applications and the outcomes of those claims;</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p><strong>Aug-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Sep-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Oct-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Nov-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Dec-15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Jan-16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>STBA Requests Received<br> <br> </strong></p></td><td><p>17,450</p></td><td><p>17,188</p></td><td><p>17,391</p></td><td><p>17,355</p></td><td><p>17,428</p></td><td><p>17,526</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>STBA Requests Primary Benefit Paid</strong><br> (where the primary benefit has been paid negating the need for an STBA)</p></td><td><p>3,420</p></td><td><p>3,984</p></td><td><p>3,890</p></td><td><p>3,688</p></td><td><p>3,971</p></td><td><p>3,699</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>STBA Requests Disallowed<br> <br> </strong></p></td><td><p>5,691</p></td><td><p>5,398</p></td><td><p>4,973</p></td><td><p>4,749</p></td><td><p>4,938</p></td><td><p>5,375</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>STBAs Awarded<br> <br> </strong></p></td><td><p>15,372</p></td><td><p>15,922</p></td><td><p>17,515</p></td><td><p>18,240</p></td><td><p>21,844</p></td><td><p>25,118</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The data provided is for Employment and Support Allowance, Incapacity Benefits, Jobseeker’s Allowance and Income Support.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-25T17:16:26.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453874/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453874/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453874/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-22","Social Security Benefits","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claims have been made for a Short Term Benefit Advance in the last six months for which data is available; and what the outcomes of those claims were.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","27645"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453875","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>The number of Employment and Support Allowance claimants with epilepsy as their main disabling condition, as at August 2015, is 44,720.</p><p> </p><p>Information on the number of people in receipt of Personal Independence Payment at 31 October 2015, by a range of conditions including epilepsy, has been published and can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a>.</p><p> </p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-25T13:53:39.123Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453875/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453875/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453875/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-22","Social Security Benefits: Epilepsy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people with epilepsy are claiming employment and support allowance and personal independence payments.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","27648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453876","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-02-25","<p>A decision to apply a sanction is not taken lightly, and claimants are given the opportunity to provide “good reason” for not complying before the decision is made. Further information is published at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-leaflet/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-how-to-keep-your-benefit-payment" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-leaflet/jobseekers-allowance-sanctions-how-to-keep-your-benefit-payment</a></p><p> </p><p>The available information for the number of Sanction appeals and reconsiderations overturned, in respect of Jobseeker’s Allowance and Employment and Support Allowance, is published via Stat-Xplore at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/" target="_blank">https://stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk</a></p><p>Guidance on how to extract the information required can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html" target="_blank">https://sw.stat-xplore.dwp.gov.uk/webapi/online-help/Getting-Started---SuperWEB2.html</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-02-25T17:12:56.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453876/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453876/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453876/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-02-22","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many benefit sanctions were issued in error and subsequently cancelled in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","27679"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453877","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-01","<p>Following the closure of the Independent Living Fund, £30 million was transferred to Welsh Government budgets to reflect the ILF’s previously-forecast expenditure in Wales. The Welsh Government is responsible for the allocation of this funding, in line with its devolved responsibilities. This funding was subsequently included in the Welsh Government’s Spending Review 2015 allocation.</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-03-01T11:25:24.813Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453877/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453877/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453877/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-22","Independent Living Fund: Wales","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what plans the Government has to provide funding to the Welsh Government until the end of the Parliament for payments under the Independent Living Fund.","false","Biography information for Ian C. Lucas","Wrexham","Ian C. Lucas","27685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454624","Attorney General","false","2016-02-25","<p>Public Legal Education is a statutory feature of the justice system and part of the Rule of Law. I have been actively involved with the Citizenship Foundation who are the UK's largest provider of public legal education for young people, I was also happy to support the recent establishment of the APPG to promote the importance of public legal education. It is my role as Solicitor General and as the Government’s pro bono champion, to help individuals become confident, effective members of society, helping them to develop an understanding of, how our society works as a democracy, our legal system, and their rights and responsibilities within it.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-25T10:39:48.107Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454624/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454624/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/454624/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-22","Law","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the Government is taking to increase public understanding of the law.","false","Biography information for Mark Menzies","Fylde","Mark Menzies","903724"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453036","Attorney General","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Crown Prosecution Service (CPS) recognises that carrying an offensive weapon, a knife or a bladed/pointed article is a serious offence as the unlawful provision and possession of weapons encourages violence and can cause serious injury and death in addition to facilitating other criminal offences.</p><p> </p><p>The CPS acts robustly to deter the carrying and use of knives and offensive weapons and has issued guidance to prosecutors on the prosecution of knife crimes. The guidance provides advice when deciding what offence to charge, the public interest considerations to apply and comments on sentencing practice.</p><p> </p><p>It has been agreed between the National Police Chiefs Council (NPCC) and the CPS that a more robust response is required in respect of youths aged 16 and 17. Guidance issued to the police by the NPCC has been shared with prosecutors to emphasise the consistency of approach of the two organisations and to underline the shared expectation that where there is sufficient evidence to provide a realistic prospect of a conviction, a prosecution should normally result.</p><p> </p><p>The CPS participates in the cross-Government Ending Gang Violence and Exploitation programme of work which includes a work-stream to reduce violence and knife crime.</p><p> </p><p>CPS data on offences charged and reaching a first hearing at magistrates’ courts shows an increased number of prosecutions for the year 2014-2015 in comparison with the previous year.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-02-25T11:24:09.777Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453036/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453036/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453036/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-02-19","Knives: Crime","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what steps the CPS is taking to ensure a higher rate of prosecution for knife crimes.","false","Biography information for Neil Coyle","Bermondsey and Old Southwark","Neil Coyle","27527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453037","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-01","<p>My Department and its partner organisations are working to make the UK the best place in Europe to innovate, patent new ideas, start and grow a business. Innovate UK delivers a range of programmes to support business-led innovation, including tools specifically designed for early-stage small and medium sized businesses.</p><p>The Spending Review protects, in cash terms, total spending on innovation through Innovate UK. We are also expanding the network of Catapult Centres, which provide valuable innovation support to businesses, and helps turn their ideas into world-beating commercial applications. There are currently nine Catapults with a further two due to open later this year.</p><p>The UK Intellectual Property Office provides a wide range of support to businesses of all sizes through its on-line tools and direct engagement, including an IP audit scheme targeted at high growth SMEs.</p><p>Support is also provided by the Government through R&amp;D tax credits, which now support between 70% and 80% of all business investment in R&amp;D. In 2013/14 there were 18,000 companies using the R&amp;D tax credit schemes, claiming a total of £1.75 billion. In addition, in the area of capital allowances, the permanent level of the Annual Investment Allowance has increased from £25,000 to £200,000 for all qualifying investment in plant and machinery made by business on or after 1 January 2016. 100% relief for capital expenditure incurred in the course of R&amp;D activities is available under the Research &amp; Development Allowance.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-01T16:26:20.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453037/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453037/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453037/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Small Businesses: Innovation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what grants and schemes his Department offers to small and medium-sized businesses to encourage innovation.","false","Biography information for Jess Phillips","Birmingham, Yardley","Jess Phillips","27516"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453038","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>As a Spending Review decision, closure of the Business Growth Service (BGS) was not subject to a formal impact assessment. We do not expect closure of the BGS to have an impact on small businesses and entrepreneurs.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-03-02T11:30:32.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453038/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453038/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453038/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Business: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, whether his Department has conducted an impact assessment on the closure of the Business Growth Service.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","27511"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453039","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-10","<p>The rates of pay for cleaners, cleaning supervisors and cleaning managers in the Department for Business Innovation and Skills are £7.93, £8.43 and £12.71 (minimum) respectively.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-03-10T16:25:00.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453039/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453039/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453039/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","27548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453040","Department for Transport","false","2016-02-29","<p>Despite the challenges of establishing an initial network, work on all 12 hydrogen refuelling stations is progressing. The first station will be fully upgraded and publically accessible by the end of this month. We expect the other stations to come on-line between March and November this year. They are located in and around London, in Swindon, Sheffield and South Wales. This will enable vehicle manufacturers to deploy their limited initial fleets of Fuel Cell Electric Vehicles and is an important first step towards a national network of 65 refuelling stations identified by UK H2Mobility.</p><p> </p>","Harrogate and Knaresborough","Andrew Jones",,"2016-02-29T17:13:39.83Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453040/answer","Biography information for Andrew Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453040/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453040/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2016-02-19","Petrol Alternatives: Hydrogen","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what progress his Department has made on the establishment of 12 hydrogen refuelling stations announced on 27 March 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27568"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453041","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>Manufacturers, distributors and retailers are legally required to inform their Local Authority Trading Standards Department if they have placed unsafe products on the market under the General Product Safety Regulations 1995. Trading Standards work with the businesses concerned to manage any corrective actions accordingly.</p><p>In December 2015, Trading Standards made my Department aware of the safety concerns relating to particular brands of tumble dryer, as part of the formal notification procedure of the EU Rapid Alert system for unsafe products. In addition, my Department has received correspondence from consumers of these products, who have been directed to Trading Standards.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T11:19:54.46Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453041/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453041/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453041/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Domestic Appliances: Fires","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what recent representations he has received on faulty tumble dryers causing fires; and when his Department was first made aware of safety concerns related to such tumble dryers.","false","Biography information for Richard Burden","Birmingham, Northfield","Richard Burden","27576"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453042","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Free Trade Agreements (FTAs) made between the EU and other countries do not automatically apply to Overseas Territories. However, the UK does work to ensure that the impact of FTAs on Overseas Territories is assessed and taken into account during negotiations.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","27494","2016-02-25T17:27:30.113Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453042/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453042/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453042/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453042/answer/previousversion/46979","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership: British Overseas Territories","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which British Overseas Territories will be included within the proposed Transatlantic Trade and Investment Partnership.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","27493"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453043","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Free Trade Agreements (FTAs) made between the EU and other countries do not automatically apply to Overseas Territories. However, the UK does work to ensure that the impact of FTAs on Overseas Territories is assessed and taken into account during negotiations.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","27493","2016-02-25T17:27:30.19Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453043/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453043/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453043/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453043/answer/previousversion/46981","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, which British Overseas Territories will be included within the Comprehensive Economic and Trade Agreement.","false","Biography information for Rob Marris","Wolverhampton South West","Rob Marris","27494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453044","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-02","<p>The average length of calls for the former Pay and Work Rights Helpline was 6 minutes 32 seconds. For the Acas Helpline which covers all call types, not just National Minimum Wage (NMW), the average length of calls is 7 minutes 54 seconds</p><p>Between April 2015 and January 2016, the latest period for which data is available, Acas have handled 768,849 calls on workplace relations and employment law.</p><p>The data collected by the Acas Helpline records the topics discussed by a caller. The figures show that there were 9,800 calls specifically related to NMW legislation and 3,700 where the caller was specifically concerned with non-payment or deductions related to the NMW. Some callers may have had queries about both subjects but due to the complexity of the data we cannot identify the number of callers that would fall into this category.</p><p>The Acas Helpline uses LanguageLine to allow real time translation with customers over the phone. Callers can request a translator at any stage in the call. A translator will join the call via a conference call, usually within seconds.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-02T11:29:23.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453044/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453044/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453044/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Employment: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 3 February 2016 to Question 25610, on minimum wage, what the average call time was to the Pay and Work Rights and ACAS helplines;  how many calls reached an ACAS operative; what definition of call was used in the data provided; and what translation facilities are available on the ACAS helpline.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453045","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>9,111 businesses in the UK, and 90 businesses in Kirklees, signed agreements with the Business Growth Service since the launch of the service in December 2014.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T11:25:29.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453045/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453045/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453045/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Business: Advisory Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, how many businesses have signed agreements with the Business Growth Service in (a) the UK and (b) Kirklees.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","27510"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453046","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>There is currently no plan to undertake a formal assessment of the outcome for workers regarding the transfer of the functions of the Pay and Work Rights Helpline to Acas.</p><p>Acas regularly monitor and test the service to help continually improve the customer journey.</p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-29T11:24:30.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453046/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453046/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453046/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","ACAS: Telephone Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, pursuant to the Answer of 11 February 2016 to Question 25611, on employment: telephone services, if he will commission an assessment of the outcome for workers of the transfer of the functions of the Pay and Work Rights Helpline to Acas from 1 April 2015.","false","Biography information for Paul Blomfield","Sheffield Central","Paul Blomfield","27210"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453047","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-03-03","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Apprenticeships are paid jobs and so their availability and level are dependent upon employers offering opportunities and recruiting apprentices. We will continue to support the growth in apprenticeships at all levels to meet our commitment to 3 million new starts in England by 2020.</p><p> </p><p>We are committed to expanding Degree Apprenticeships, which combine a high quality degree with an apprenticeship. Higher and Degree Apprenticeships are widening access to the professions, providing the higher level technical skills employers need to improve productivity and giving young people an equally valid career route to purely university-based courses.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p><p>All Apprenticeship Starts by Level (2014/15 and 2015/16 - Reported to Date)</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Level</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2014/15</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>2015/16</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong> </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Full Year</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>August to October</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Level 2</p></td><td><p>298,280</p></td><td><p>86,620</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Level 3</p></td><td><p>181,760</p></td><td><p>60,140</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Level 4</p></td><td><p>7,090</p></td><td><p>2,880</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Level 5</p></td><td><p>12,590</p></td><td><p>3,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Level 6</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>240</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Higher Apprenticeships</p></td><td><p>19,770</p></td><td><p>6,320</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Total Apprenticeships</p></td><td><p><strong>499,900</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>153,100</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-03-03T17:30:01.877Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453047/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453047/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453047/answer","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453047/answer/previousversion/46973","Biography information for Nick Boles","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Apprentices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the number of apprentices at each of the apprenticeship educational levels 2 to 6 whom the Government plans to be part of its target of three million apprentices by 2020.","false","Biography information for Ms Angela Eagle","Wallasey","Ms Angela Eagle","27238"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453048","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>Neodymium and dysprosium are rare earth elements, which means that they are included on the EU’s list of critical raw materials because of their high economic importance and high supply risk. Tellurium is not on that list but the Government is aware of its scarcity and importance to manufacturing of alloys and some electronic equipment. The UK is working with European partners and others in global organisations to ensure that there is sufficient supply in the future that is available in accordance global trade rules.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:29:57.76Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453048/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453048/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453048/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453048/answer/previousversion/46974","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Metals","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what assessment he has made of the security of supply of (a) the rare earths neodymium and dysprosium and (b) tellurium.","false","Biography information for Sir Nicholas Soames","Mid Sussex","Sir Nicholas Soames","27339"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453049","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-25","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) has held no specific discussions with my Rt hon Friend the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the effect of the Government’s policy on biomass on the availability of UK-produced wood supplies to UK industries.</p><p> </p><p>BIS is coordinating discussions between senior leaders in the industrial biotechnology, synthetic biology, chemicals, medicines manufacturing and agri-tech sectors, to consider how these industries can work together, alongside the UK’s excellent science and technology base, to build a strong and growing bioeconomy. These discussions are likely to include the availability of biomass feedstocks and their impact on specific sectors.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-25T17:25:31.213Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453049/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453049/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453049/answer","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453049/answer/previousversion/46975","Biography information for Anna Soubry","26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Timber: Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change on the effect of the Government's policy on biomass on the availability of UK-produced wood supplies to UK industries.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","27352"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453050","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>Cabinet Office officials have been working with Local Enterprise Partnerships (LEPs) - including the hon. Member’s LEP, Leeds City Region - and the Big Lottery Fund to agree European Social Fund match-funding arrangements. This funding will invest in local projects tackling the root causes of poverty, promoting social inclusion, local jobs and growth. Social enterprises and charities are well placed to get involved in these opportunities.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T11:22:49.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453050/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453050/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453050/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Local Enterprise Partnerships: Social Enterprises","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with local enterprise partnerships on supporting social enterprises.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","27378"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453051","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-26","<p><strong> </strong></p><p> </p><p>In July 2015 my Rt hon Friend the Prime Minister appointed Julie Deane OBE to look at what more could be done to support the self-employed. Julie Deane’s report ‘Self-Employment Review’ was published on 14th February and can be viewed at <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/500358/ind-16-2-self-employment-review.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/500358/ind-16-2-self-employment-review.pdf</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government is reviewing her recommendations in regard to this area carefully.</p><p> </p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Grantham and Stamford","Nick Boles",,"2016-02-26T14:09:33.85Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453051/answer","Biography information for Nick Boles","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453051/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Self-employed: Parental Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what steps he is taking to improve access to parental leave for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","27413"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453052","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The arrangements in place for the Crown Transformation Programme were specific to this significant programme which encompassed the entire Crown network and which was a directly government funded investment programme. How Post Office handles business as usual changes to its branch estate is an operational matter for it. Post Office has a Code of Practice for changes to the network (such as relocations of branches) and this includes a role for Citizen’s Advice.</p>","Mid Norfolk","George Freeman",,"2016-02-29T11:22:07.763Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453052/answer","Biography information for George Freeman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453052/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Post Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, for what reasons the process for including Citizens Advice as the statutory consumer watchdog differs for changes to Crown post offices outside compared with those within the Crown Transformation Programme.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","27410"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453053","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The future of the Lochaber smelter is largely a devolved matter, but the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) has discussed Rio Tinto’s strategic review with the Scottish Government and will maintain these contacts as the situation develops. There have been no direct contacts with Rio Tinto, but BIS officials have discussed this matter with the Aluminium Federation, which represents the aluminium industry in the UK.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T11:28:20.257Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453053/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453053/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Rio Tinto Alcan: Lochaber","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he (a) has had and (b) plans to have with Rio Tinto on that company's strategic review of its smelter operations in Lochaber.","false","Biography information for Ian Blackford","Ross, Skye and Lochaber","Ian Blackford","27411"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453054","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Department for Business, Innovation and Skills continues to have discussions with businesses and their representatives. They have told us that there is strong appetite in the private sector to fill the gap in the market and develop sustainable offers of support.</p>","Broxtowe","Anna Soubry",,"2016-02-29T11:26:19.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453054/answer","Biography information for Anna Soubry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453054/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2016-02-19","Small Businesses: Government Assistance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Innovation and Skills, what discussions he has had with social enterprises and other small and medium-sized enterprises about the potential effect of the closure of the Growth Accelerator Programme.","false","Biography information for Mr Barry Sheerman","Huddersfield","Mr Barry Sheerman","27418"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453055","Cabinet Office","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government is currently considering the recommendations made by the Law Commissions in their interim report of 4 February. This is a wide-ranging report that covers a number of complex issues and it is important that the Government give the report due consideration before a formal response is made.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2016-02-24T16:12:43.687Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453055/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453055/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-19","Elections: Legislation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, when the Government plans to respond to the Law Commission's recommendations for change to UK electoral law published on 4 February 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","27583"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453056","Cabinet Office","false","2016-03-03","<p>The pay range for directly employed London cleaning staff is £19,988 - £24,430 per annum.</p><p>The rates of pay for cleaning staff employed by our Facilities Management contractors around the country range from £6.70 per hour to £7.62 per hour, depending on the contract.</p><p>The pay of contracted cleaners will increase to the National Living Wage when that is introduced in April. As the living wage increases the minimum paid to cleaners will also increase.</p>","West Suffolk","Matthew Hancock",,"2016-03-03T13:17:00.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453056/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453056/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-02-19","Cabinet Office: Cleaning Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what the rate of pay is for cleaners in his Department.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","27550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453057","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-26","<p>A NISM is a notification issued to the electricity market to ask power stations to make more generation available for a short, specified, period of time. It doesn't mean demand is about to outstrip supply, only that National Grid would like a larger cushion of spare capacity in the short term.</p><p> </p><p>DECC has not made an assessment of the impact of NISMS on GDP. There have been 2 NISMs since 2010 and these have only lasted a few hours on each occasion and have had virtually no impact on consumer bills.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-26T14:09:09.72Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453057/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453057/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-19","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she has made an assessment of the potential effect on UK GDP of the National Grid issuing Notification of Inadequate System Margin notices; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","27566"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453058","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>An impact assessment for the Carbon Price Floor (CPF) was published in the March 2011 <em>Overview of Tax Legislation and Rates</em> (starting on p.141) which can be accessed via the following link, <a href="http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130129110402/http:/cdn.hm-treasury.gov.uk/2011budget_taxation_overview.pdf." target="_blank">http://webarchive.nationalarchives.gov.uk/20130129110402/http:/cdn.hm-treasury.gov.uk/2011budget_taxation_overview.pdf.</a></p><p> </p><p>A further impact assessment was published in a <em>Tax and Information Impact Note</em> in March 2014 and can be accessed via the following the link, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/carbon-price-floor-reform" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/carbon-price-floor-reform</a>.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-25T17:29:00.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453058/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453058/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Taxation: Environment Protection","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will place in the library a copy of the impact assessment of the carbon price floor mechanism.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","27559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453059","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>Like any employer HM Treasury does not comment on individual personnel matters. Special Advisor salaries are determined accurately to the responsibilities and seniority of each individual role.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-25T15:18:57.647Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453059/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453059/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Ministerial Policy Advisers: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 10 February 2016 to Question 26025, for what reason Thea Rogers' salary increased from £69,250 in 2014 to £98,000 in 2015.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","27582"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453060","HM Treasury","false","2016-03-17","<p>The information is not available in the form requested.</p>The Government’s new settlement means that EU nationals whose children live abroad will ultimately receive Child Benefit at a rate that reflects the conditions – including the standard of living and child benefit paid – of the country where their child lives. This will restore fairness to the system. Meanwhile, Child Tax Credit is being phased out, and we do not have to pay the new Universal Credit for children living in other countries. That means as Universal Credit is fully rolled out, the only benefit we will pay for children living in other Member States will be the indexed rate of Child Benefit.<p> </p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds","27522","2016-03-17T16:12:44.297Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453060/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453060/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Child Benefit: Immigrants","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many migrants residing in the UK claim benefits on behalf of children living abroad; and what the value is of such claims by country of residence of the child.","false","Biography information for Rachel Reeves","Leeds West","Rachel Reeves","27574"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453061","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Government agrees that market-wide credit data sharing is key to effective affordability assessments in the high-cost, short-term credit market. In February 2014 the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) asked the payday lending industry to identify and remove any blockages to real-time data sharing as a matter of urgency. The FCA reports that there has been substantial recent progress made by the industry in this area. Over 90% of high-cost, short-term lenders by market share are meeting the FCA’s expectations to share data in real-time.</p><p> </p><p>The FCA expects that the proportion of firms using real-time data sharing to further increase by the time the authorisation process is complete for most high-cost short-term credit firms. The FCA will continue to monitor progress to keep this momentum, and ensure that there continues to be improvement in this area.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-24T16:17:16.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453061/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453061/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking to ensure that there is full market participation in real-time data-sharing in the short-term credit market.","false","Biography information for Meg Hillier","Hackney South and Shoreditch","Meg Hillier","27579"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453062","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Along with most major economies in the world, the UK has a territorial tax system that charges corporation tax on profits earned from economic activity carried out here.</p><p> </p><p>The UK cannot tax profits arising from sales in the UK to the extent that those profits are generated by activities carried on outside the UK.</p><p> </p><p>Multinational companies’ profits are taxed in accordance with internationally agreed principles. The current international tax rules were first developed in the 1920s and the UK is playing a leading role in updating them so they are fit for purpose in today’s modern globalising economy.</p><p> </p><p>Tax avoidance and aggressive tax planning by multinationals requires a coordinated approach to come up with effective solutions.</p><p> </p><p>The UK will continue to be at the forefront of multilateral action through the G20, the Organisation for Economic Co-Operation and Development (OECD) and the EU to reform the international tax standards to prevent aggressive tax planning by multinationals.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-29T17:05:58.963Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453062/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453062/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Multinational Companies: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he plans to take to ensure that all UK-registered companies are subject to the same tax provisions as their UK competitors providing the same services to the same customer base regardless of the official locations of the European subsidiaries of such companies.","false","Biography information for Tom Elliott","Fermanagh and South Tyrone","Tom Elliott","27529"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453063","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2016-02-26","<p>Demand Side Balancing Response (DSBR) is part of National Grid’s Contingency Balancing Reserve. Under the DSBR, firms bid for contracts to reduce their demand from the grid when instructed by National Grid in return for an agreed utilisation fee.</p><p> </p><p>DECC has not made an assessment of the impact of DSBR on GDP; DSBR is small (133 MW in 15/16), runs infrequently and is entirely voluntary.</p><p> </p><p>Since the service commenced in winter 14/15, National Grid has only instructed on one occasion, instructing a total of 42.9MW, for which participants were paid a pre-contracted utilisation fee.</p><p> </p><p> </p><p> </p>","South Northamptonshire","Andrea Leadsom",,"2016-02-26T14:08:23.803Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453063/answer","Biography information for Andrea Leadsom","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453063/answer",,,,,"63","Energy and Climate Change","Energy and Climate Change","2016-02-19","National Grid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Energy and Climate Change, whether she has made an assessment of the potential effect on UK GDP of the National Grid using its demand side balancing reserve powers; and if she will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","27564"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453064","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Prudential Regulation Authority's (PRA) proposed rules allowing ring-fenced bodies to pay dividends to other entities in the parent group are entirely consistent with the ring-fencing legislation and the Independent Commission on Banking’s recommendations. The PRA has the power to prevent these payments if they deem that they would negatively impact on the viability of the ring-fenced bank.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:52:53.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453064/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453064/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for the effectiveness of the ring-fence between retail and investment banking of the Prudential Regulation Authority's proposal to allow ring-fenced bodies to pay dividends to other entities in the parent group.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27453"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453065","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Since May 2015, in order to ensure the smooth implementation of ring-fencing, ministers and HMT officials have met with regulators, banks, banking organisations, trustees of bank pension funds and HMRC.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:53:26.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453065/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453065/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453065/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Banks","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what meetings (a) Ministers and (b) officials of his Department have had on the implementation of the ring-fence between retail and investment banking since May 2015.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27454"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453066","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government is confident that the Prudential Regulation Authority's proposed rules on ring-fencing are beneficial for financial system resilience. These are fully consistent with the Banking Reform Act (2013), and are necessary to ensure the full and timely implementation of the legislation.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:46:33.903Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453066/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453066/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for financial system resilience of the Prudential Regulation Authority's proposed rules on ringfencing; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27449"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453067","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Ring-fencing will introduce a high degree of operational and economic independence between core retail banks and broader financial markets. The Independent Commission on Banking in 2011 recommended the ring-fencing of retail from investment banking to promote financial system resilience, and the Government agreed with this recommendation.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:47:46.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453067/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453067/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453067/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the likely effectiveness of the ring-fence between retail and investment banking in reducing the interconnectedness of the UK financial system; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27450"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453068","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>Ring-fencing insulates ring-fenced banks from shocks originating elsewhere in the global financial system, and makes ring-fenced banks simpler so that monitoring and supervision is easier. The PRA are putting in place rules to ensure that the ring-fenced bank can effectively manage its liquidity.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:51:27.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453068/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453068/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what recent assessment he has made of the potential effectiveness of the ring-fence between retail and investment banking in reducing funding risk in the UK financial system; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27451"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453069","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Prudential Regulation Authority's proposed rules allowing cross-selling and cross-lending between ring-fenced bodies and other entities in the parent group in some circumstances are consistent with the ring-fencing legislation and the Independent Commission on Banking’s recommendations. These agency arrangements simply allow for the customer to access products provided by the wider banking group within their local premises.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:52:23.073Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453069/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453069/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Financial Services","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the implications for the effectiveness of the ring-fence between retail and investment banking of the Prudential Regulation Authority's proposal to allow cross-selling and cross-lending between ring-fenced bodies and other entities in the parent group in some circumstances.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","27452"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453070","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-02-24","<p>The Spending Review recognised that demographic changes are leading to increased demand for adult social care. To support those most in need, we provided a social care package of up to £3.5 billion by 2019-20. This package includes giving all councils with responsibility for adult social care the option of an extra 2% council tax precept, as long as the precept is spent on adult social care. It is for Redcar and Cleveland to decide if they wish to take up this flexibility.</p><p> </p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-02-24T17:30:30.797Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453070/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453070/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-02-19","Local Government Finance: Redcar and Cleveland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how he plans to respond to the recent request from the Leader of Redcar and Cleveland Council for a transitional sum of £1 million in lieu of raising the adult social care precept.","false","Biography information for Tom Blenkinsop","Middlesbrough South and East Cleveland","Tom Blenkinsop","27478"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453071","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-24","<p>Tax treaties are negotiated by HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) officials, reporting to Treasury Ministers.</p><p> </p><p>The UK has a large number of tax treaties which includes treaties with developing countries. Some of those treaties require updating and HMRC officials actively seek engagement with developing countries to that end. For example, there are ongoing negotiations with Ghana, prospective negotiations with Nepal and negotiations with Lesotho and Malawi are close to conclusion.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC publishes the programme of tax treaty negotiations and news of signed treaties at: https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/double-taxation-agreements-developments-and-planned-negotiations.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-24T16:17:01.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453071/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453071/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453071/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Double Taxation: Developing Countries","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether his Department plans to renegotiate tax treaties with developing countries.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","27248"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453072","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Government takes the enforcement of National Minimum Wage very seriously. Any worker who believes that they are being paid below the minimum wage should make a complaint to the Acas helpline on 0300 123 1100. HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) respond to every complaint that is referred to them by the Acas helpline. Additionally, HMRC collate and analyse data from various sources in order to identify those employers who are potentially more likely to be underpaying National Minimum Wage, so that they can undertake targeted enforcement against those employers.</p><p> </p><p>The Government has increased annual funding of National Minimum Wage enforcement by nearly 60% since 2013/14, providing a budget of £13.2m in 2015/16. This has enabled a significant expansion of resources dedicated to enforcing the minimum wage; there are currently 237 staff in HMRC's National Minimum Wage teams, up from 151 at the start of 2013/14. HMRC have also reviewed their ways of working to ensure a more efficient and effective service for workers.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-29T17:04:08.407Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453072/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453072/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Minimum Wage","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 15 February 2016 to Question 26319 on the national minimum wage, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the increase in the arrears identified between April 2015 and November 2015; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","27319"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453073","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) retains records of tax credit claims for the tax year of the claim plus five years.</p><p> </p><p>The length of time HMRC is required to retain other tax credit records is depends on the type of record retained. Retention periods for individual documents can be found at:</p><p><a href="http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/manuals/tcmanual/tcm0322580.htm" target="_blank">http://www.hmrc.gov.uk/manuals/tcmanual/tcm0322580.htm</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-02-29T17:04:57.39Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453073/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453073/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, for how long HM Revenue and Customs is required to keep records on individual tax credit cases.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","27416"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453074","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Government is committed to making the aspiration of home ownership a reality for as many households as possible. At the Spending Review the Government announced a series of measures which will help people become homeowners. These include plans to deliver 200,000 Starter Homes and 135,000 Shared Ownership homes; increasing the value of Help to Buy equity loans in London to 40% from 25% and extending the Help to Buy: Equity Loan scheme for a further year to 2021.</p><p> </p><p>These schemes are also supported by the Help to Buy: ISA, through which the Government tops up mortgage deposit savings for first time buyers by up to £3,000.</p><p> </p><p>Decisions around the availability of individual mortgage loans are commercial decisions for lenders, including what evidence is required to validate income. The Government does not seek to intervene in these decisions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-26T12:41:39.397Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453074/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453074/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Self-employed: Owner Occupation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to support self-employed people who want to buy their own home.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","27414"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453075","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-26","<p>The Government is committed to ensuring that the mortgage market delivers for creditworthy borrowers.</p><p> </p><p>On 1 December 2015 the Government launched the Help to Buy: ISA to help all first time buyers saving for their first home.</p><p> </p><p>Beyond the requirements set out in the regulations, decisions around the availability of individual mortgage loans are commercial decisions for lenders, including what evidence is required to validate income. The Government does not seek to intervene in these decisions.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-26T12:39:56.913Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453075/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453075/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Self-employed: Mortgages","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps the Government is taking to improve access to mortgages for self-employed people.","false","Biography information for Susan Elan Jones","Clwyd South","Susan Elan Jones","27415"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453076","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The issues raised are a matter for the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA) who are operationally independent from Government.</p><p> </p><p>The questions have been passed on to the FCA. The FCA will reply directly to the Honorable Member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T16:03:02.04Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453076/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453076/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453076/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Investment Trusts","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to the Oral Contribution of the Economic Secretary to the Treasury of 1 February 2016, Official Report, column 748, what further progress has been made on investigations into the Connaught Income Fund, series 1.","false","Biography information for David Hanson","Delyn","Mr David Hanson","27426"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453077","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-24","<p>The latest regional public sector employment survey figures are available online at: http://www.ons.gov.uk/ons/rel/pse/public-sector-employment/q3-2015/index.html</p>","Chelsea and Fulham","Greg Hands",,"2016-02-24T17:15:59.153Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453077/answer","Biography information for Greg Hands","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453077/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453077/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Regional Planning and Development: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, pursuant to the Answer of 12 February 2016 to Question 26203, if he will provide the number of publicly-funded jobs related directly to the Northern Powerhouse located in (a) Cumbria, (b) Northern England, (c) London and (d) other parts of England.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","27475"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453078","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>China’s foreign exchange reserves have fallen over the past year, down $582.5bn since the start of 2015. However, the stock of reserves still remains sizeable, standing at $3.23 trillion. The UK’s exports to China have increased by 85% since 2010 but are still only 5% of total UK trade.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin",,"2016-02-29T15:55:23.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453078/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453078/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453078/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Economic Situation: China","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the fall in China's foreign currency reserves on the UK economy.","false","Biography information for Julie Cooper","Burnley","Julie Cooper","27377"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453079","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>As at 21 February 2016 Concentrix had closed around 440,000 cases. Around 390,000 of these resulted in no amendment to the award. Around 50,000 awards have been amended, though HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold information on how many of these were cancelled and how many adjusted.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not separate out the number of awards that were amended for error and from the number amended for fraud.</p><p> </p><p>On appeals, I refer the member to the answer I provided on 15 February 2016 to question 26041.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","27383","2016-02-29T17:02:59.11Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453079/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453079/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453079/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what proportion of tax credit investigations carried out by Concentrix under its contract with his Department have resulted in findings of (a) fraud and (b) error in the claim.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","27382"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453080","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>As at 21 February 2016 Concentrix had closed around 440,000 cases. Around 390,000 of these resulted in no amendment to the award. Around 50,000 awards have been amended, though HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) does not hold information on how many of these were cancelled and how many adjusted.</p><p> </p><p>HMRC does not separate out the number of awards that were amended for error and from the number amended for fraud.</p><p> </p><p>On appeals, I refer the member to the answer I provided on 15 February 2016 to question 26041.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","27382","2016-02-29T17:02:59.22Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453080/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453080/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453080/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Welfare Tax Credits","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many tax credit investigations carried out by Concentrix under its contract with his Department have resulted in (a) no change in and (b) withdrawal of the tax credit award; and how many decisions to withdraw such awards were appealed successfully.","false","Biography information for Ronnie Cowan","Inverclyde","Ronnie Cowan","27383"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453081","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-25","<p>It is not possible to disaggregate tax receipts by commodity therefore, a figure for the revenue accrued by the Exchequer from taxes levied on coal cannot be provided.</p><p> </p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-02-25T17:30:12.863Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453081/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453081/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453081/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Coal: Taxation","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how much has accrued to the public purse from the taxation of coal in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Philip Davies","Shipley","Philip Davies","27406"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453082","HM Treasury","false","2016-02-29","<p>The Chancellor set out the government’s view on the challenges facing the UK economy in a speech on 7 January. The transcript of the speech is available from www.gov.uk/government/speeches/chancellor-on-challenges-facing-uk-economy-in-2016. The Chancellor and other Ministers meet regularly with regulators and the Bank of England. In addition, the Bank of England’s Financial Stability Report sets out an analysis, which can be found here:</p><p>http://www.bankofengland.co.uk/publications/Pages/fsr/2015/dec.aspx</p><p>The Financial Policy Committee’s (FPC) stress test results in December 2015 suggest that the major UK banks would be resilient to a sustained commodity price downturn.</p><p> </p><p>The UK now has a robust system of financial regulation, where the regulators have clear objectives and powers to deal with risks to the financial sector. The Government established the FPC to identify, monitor and address systemic risks to financial stability.</p>","West Worcestershire","Harriett Baldwin","27298 ; 27299 ; 27300","2016-02-29T16:02:04.707Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453082/answer","Biography information for Harriett Baldwin","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453082/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/453082/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-02-19","Oil: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with which financial institutions on the energy exposure of such institutions in response to the falling price of oil.","false","Biography information for Philip Boswell","Coatbridge, Chryston and Bellshill","Phil Boswell","27297"
